  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (dirty money) appear legal by disguising its true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers intended to conceal the illicit source of the funds.\n\nIn China, money laundering is strictly prohibited under the Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China, which was enacted to prevent and combat money laundering activities and to maintain financial order. The law imposes obligations on financial institutions to establish and implement anti-money laundering measures, and it provides for penalties for those who engage in money laundering activities.\n\nThe Chinese government is committed to combating financial crimes, including money laundering, and has enacted strict laws and regulations to prevent and punish such activities. The legal framework is designed to protect the integrity of the financial system and to ensure that financial institutions are not used as conduits for illicit funds.",
